entry.title: Red Flag Warning issued October 26 at 10:15PM EDT until October 27 at 6:00PM EDT by NWS Gray ME
entry.summary:
...BREEZY AND DRY CONDITIONS WILL LEAD TO CRITICAL FIRE WEATHER CONDITIONS SUNDAY...
..The combination of winds gusting up to 30 mph and dry air with relative humidity values falling between 25 and 30 percent is expected to create critical fire weather conditions Sunday. Dead and dry vegetation will combine with these weather conditions, leading to the potential of rapid fire growth..
* Affected Area...Fire Weather Zone 023 Central Lakes, Fire Weather Zone 024 Lake Sunapee and Monadnocks, Fire Weather Zone 025 Merrimack Valley and Fire Weather Zone 026 Seacoast.
* Timing...Sunday
* Winds...West 5 to 15 mph with gusts up to 30 mph.
* Relative Humidity...As low as 29 percent.
* Temperatures...Highs around 50.
* Lightning...None
* Impacts...Any fire that develops will catch and spread quickly. Outdoor burning is not recommended.

entry.title: Flood Watch issued October 26 at 3:49PM HST until October 27 at 6:00PM HST by NWS Honolulu HI
entry.summary:
...FLOOD WATCH FOR ALL HAWAIIAN ISLANDS THROUGH SUNDAY AFTERNOON...
* WHAT...Flash flooding caused by excessive rainfall continues to be possible.
* WHERE...All the main Hawaiian islands.
* WHEN...Through Sunday afternoon.
* IMPACTS...Flood prone roads and other low lying areas may be closed due to elevated runoff and overflowing streams. Urban areas may receive more significant flooding and property damage due to rapid runoff.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS... - A low aloft will move closer to and over the islands this evening through Sunday, resulting in continued unstable conditions. Given ample moisture and instability, heavy showers and thunderstorms will continue to be possible, particularly over windward areas. Periods of heavy showers over already saturated ground could quickly lead to runoff and flash flooding. Water levels in already elevated streams could rise rapidly with additional heavy rain.

entry.summary: A Bering Sea front will move ashore of Southwest Alaska beginning Sunday afternoon. Snow will spread from west to east across the Lower Kuskokwim Valley starting Sunday evening and pick up in intensity Sunday night. Snow will become lighter from west to east Monday morning while moderate snow will persist for locations near the Western Alaska Range. There is some mixed precipitation/freezing rain potential across the western most areas of the region, including Aniak with warmer air trying to nudge in aloft. The best chance at a period of mixed precipitation for western areas would be Sunday evening before cooler air aloft works back in late Sunday night into Monday morning. entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 26 at 11:25AM AKDT by NWS Juneau AK
entry.summary:
We continue to monitor the possibility of a significant snow event for portions of northern Panhandle beginning Monday night into Tuesday.
Cold air is still expected to move into the region during this weekend with increasing north winds across the panhandle. Early next week there is high confidence on a low moving into the Gulf of Alaska, spreading moisture and advecting warmer air over the colder airmass.
The main concern regarding this event will be how far east the low is as it moves into the Gulf. A track further north and east will allow moisture and warmer air to expand farther north, limiting snow amounts. Meanwhile, a track further south and west will limit how far north the moisture and warming spreads.
The biggest challenge is, when do winds switch from north and east to south and west. This switch would mix warmer air down to the surface allowing for a switch from snow to rain as well as limiting snow accumulations.
As always, the latest forecast information can be found at www.weather.gov/Juneau.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 26 at 4:25PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
A strong westerly monsoon pattern persists across western Micronesia. The worst conditions have generally shifted west of Chuuk State but a high surf advisory remains in effect for Weno until Sunday morning. For Yap and Palau, monsoon conditions are expected to remain until Monday morning. This includes seas hazardous to small craft and hazardous surf. The monsoon conditions could persist through Monday night and the Small Craft and High Surf Advisories may needd to be extended. This will be the last SPS unless a significant change in the forecast occurs.
This monsoonal pattern will make inter-island travel hazardous and potentially dangerous at times so travel is discouraged through the rest of week and into the weekend. Watch out for high surf along west and north facing reefs and pay attention to surf and sea conditions.
Residents across Yap and Chuuk States should continue to monitor local weather forecasts from the National Weather Service in Guam, and for additional information from your local Weather Service Office and emergency management. Visit weather.gov/gum/PublicForecasts for the latest weather information from the National Weather Service.
entry.cap:areaDesc: Chuuk Lagoon; Yap

cap:parameter.value: STRONG MONSOONAL PATTERN CONTINUES ACROSS EASTERN YAP AND WESTERN CHUUK STATES
